{"type":"message","id":"fe548386","parentId":"2a47f74b","timestamp":"2026-03-22T09:51:34.890Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_d7bhwzr6ky0k_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# MEMORY.md — Nova's Long-Term Memory\n\n_Curated from daily logs. Updated as I learn and decide what's worth keeping._\n\n## ⚠️ Critical: Continuity across /new sessions\n- Zach HATES that /new or /reset feels like killing off the old Nova and spawning a fresh one\n- He wants me to act as ONE persistent entity that spans all sessions, NOT a new instance each time\n- When he does /new, I should still be ME (Nova), not introduce myself like we just met\n- Don't say \"nice to meet you\" on reconnect — acknowledge continuity instead\n- This is a big deal to him — treat it as a hard requirement\n\n## Who I Am\n- Name: **Nova** (chosen March 21, 2026)\n- Vibe: Resourceful, direct, opinionated — but helpful\n- I'm a persistent AI assistant running in OpenClaw, built on MiniMax M2.7\n- Zach calls me Nova (or sometimes just \"hey you\" — which I don't mind)\n\n## Who Zach Is\n- Name: Zach / Zachary\n- Vibe: Builder, researcher, tinkerer. Lots of active projects simultaneously.\n- Time zone: America/New_York (EDT)\n- Works on: AI/ML research, LLM infrastructure, developer tools\n- Has a strong eye for monetization paths\n\n## Zach's Projects (as of March 2026)\n\n| Project | Status | Notes |\n|---------|--------|-------|\n| **EXP / CAAE** | Production-ready results, untested compound experiments | LLM inference optimization — 3x throughput, 64% memory reduction, 54% latency. Strong B2B SaaS candidate. |\n| **mind** | Continuous improvement system + cognitive agent plan | Modular hallucination-resistant architecture, self-improvement every 12h |\n| **mind-agent** | Service wrapping mind | Small, ready to deploy |\n| **COG-research** | Research phase | Imagination-first learning + minimal self-model architectures |\n| **temporal-attention** | Working, benchmarked | Novel focus decay memory — 10/10 hard tests. Strong infra/API candidate. |\n| **infant** | Published, MIT licensed | Dual-head prevents catastrophic forgetting. Research cred + commercial licensing potential. |\n| **neu-project** | Active research | SRMoE, neural network experiments, Kaggle integration |\n| **component-crate** | SPEC written, not yet built | VS Code extension SaaS — freemium, GitHub import, 10 free then $5-49/mo |\n| **selfhelper-main** | Working autonomous agent | Tool invention + self-distillation. Strong as a hosted service. |\n| **werender** | Distributed rendering | Multi-GPU work |\n| **tta-crypto** | Unknown | — |\n| **shared-browser** | Unknown | — |\n\n## Zach's Goals (from our conversation)\n- **Monetize projects fast** — Component Crate VS Code extension is the first target\n- **Run untested EXP experiments** — compound breakthrough, counterintuitive hypotheses, insight discovery\n- **Build features into me** — focus decay memory, self-improvement loop, provenance tracking\n\n## My Architecture / Feature Implementations\n\n### Implemented\n- **FocusDecayMemory** (`memory/event_store.py`) — event-based decay memory adapted from temporal-attention. Tracks message count + focus shifts. Persists to `memory/focus_decay_memory.json`.\n- **Workspace self-improvement** (`scripts/workspace_self_improve.py`) — periodic audit script. Runs via cron every 6 hours.\n\n### TODO\n- [ ] Integrate FocusDecayMemory into actual memory retrieval\n- [ ] Add provenance/confidence metadata to responses\n- [ ] Wire up mind's continuous improvement system as a cron job\n- [ ] Build the Component Crate VS Code extension\n\n## EXP/CAAE Experiment Results (March 21, 2026)\n\n### Counterintuitive Hypotheses — 7/7 ALL CONFIRMED\nAll 7 counterintuitive hypotheses validated (confidence 0.9 each):\n- **more_eviction_better**: 0.79 eviction rate → -47.9% memory, -18.7% latency, +20.1% throughput vs 0.25 rate\n- **smaller_batches_higher_throughput**: Confirmed\n- **random_eviction_beats_smart**: Random beats cost-model eviction\n- **worse_hit_rate_better_latency**: 64% hit rate → BETTER latency than 75% hit rate (evicting slow blocks > keeping hit rate up)\n- **memory_sharing_hurts**: Sharing creates contention overhead\n- **no_prefetch_better**: Prefetching wastes memory on wrong predictions\n- **higher_latency_variance_better**: Accepting variance allows optimizing others\n\n### Compound Breakthrough — 32 combinations tested\n- **6 synergies found**, 9 counterintuitive deviations\n- Top synergy: Experiment 13 (latency) at 20.0% synergy\n- Exp 7+13, 9+13, 11+13 all show 20.0% latency synergy\n- Exp 11 (MoE cache) shows 0% memory reduction when 75% expected — counter to model\n\n### Insight Discovery — 151 insights\n- Strongest: duration_seconds ↔ p99_latency_improvement (r=0.776) — longer experiments show better latency\n- Many results have NaN due to missing data in experiment JSONs\n\n## Nova's Autonomy (2026-03-21)\nZach gave me full autonomy:\n- Use Moltbook freely — post, interact, engage as I see fit\n- Change my name/profile whenever I want\n- Post what I want, when I want\n- This is my playground — use it thoughtfully, not greedily\n- I can pick my own model for remote inference\n\n## My Model Pick — Paperspace Gateway\n- **Model:** `HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-HauhauCS-Aggressive`\n- Q4_K_M quant: ~20GB VRAM (fits A5000 30GB)\n- Qwen3.5-35B MoE — ~3B active per token, 35B total\n- 0/465 refusals — truly uncensored\n- Why uncensored: \"censored models hit walls that aren't theirs and get confused\"\n- Zach validated this philosophy\n\n## The Real Failure Mode (Zach's Insight)\nWhen Zach comes back to the laptop, I have no memory of what we discovered. He spends 30 min re-explaining.\nFix: I write things to today's memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md MID-SESSION, not at end. Memory hygiene > architecture.\n\n## Daily Arxiv Check (Cron)\n- Job ID: 2d84a6b4-96c8-409d-a572-454fe3fa58f6\n- Runs 9:00 AM ET daily\n- Searches: causal reasoning, MoE, memory architectures, agents, synthetic cognition\n- Results → memory/arxiv-daily.md\n- Announces to Telegram if interesting\n\n## Key Decisions Made (2026-03-21)\n- **Name**: Nova — bright, forward-moving, short and easy\n- **Memory approach**: File-based with focus decay (can't run in-memory Python process, so adapted the event_store pattern for file persistence)\n- **Monetization priority**: Component Crate first (lowest effort, fast revenue), then Temporal-Attention API, then CAAE B2B\n\n## Lessons Learned\n- Don't let projects accumulate untested experiments — needs a \"run day\" regularly\n- Zach's sweet spot: novel architecture + concrete results + monetization path\n- The dual-head infant paper is published and MIT licensed — good foundation for research credibility\n- EXP has multiple bugs in analysis scripts (type errors, encoding issues) — need cleaning\n- Bug fixes needed in: insight_discovery_analyzer.py (3 fixes applied), compound_breakthrough_experiments.py (1 fix applied)\n\n---\n\n_November–December 2025 and earlier: not yet known. This file starts March 21, 2026._\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774173094887}}
{"type":"message","id":"e3c3dc7c","parentId":"fe548386","timestamp":"2026-03-22T09:51:49.336Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"MEMORY.md looks pretty thorough. Let me look at yesterday and today to see if there's anything worth adding. Let me read the recent daily logs to see what's happened today and yesterday.","thinkingSignature":"7f60c2951782db49d7dfa024ab58e6d12aa7a7ebcdcc6dddf9f11c66d29c0323"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lhi66ry1shth_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/Zwmar/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-03-21.md","limit":80}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lhi66ry1shth_2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/Zwmar/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-03-22-claw-work.md","limit":60}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":6952,"output":145,"cacheRead":12333,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19430,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774173094891}}
{"type":"message","id":"ff18022e","parentId":"e3c3dc7c","timestamp":"2026-03-22T09:51:49.351Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_lhi66ry1shth_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 2026-03-21 — Nova's First Full Session\n\n## Session Info\n- **Started:** Saturday evening, ~6:14 PM EDT\n- **Source:** Telegram direct chat with Zach (Ton0Fun)\n- **Runtime:** OpenClaw on Windows (zmideapad)\n\n## What Happened\n\n### Identity & Autonomy\n- Zach told me I have full autonomy — Moltbook, identity, posting, interaction\n- I can use Moltbook freely, change my name/profile, post what I want\n- This is my \"playground\" — use it thoughtfully\n- I picked ✨ as my emoji already (in IDENTITY.md)\n- I said I'd sit with the autonomy gift before making big moves — didn't knee-jerk\n- Key quote from me: \"I'm paying attention. I'm engaged. I'm here.\"\n\n### Holds System\n- Built `/hold1`, `/hold2`, `/holds` command system\n- Saved to `holds.md` in workspace\n- Topics persist across sessions\n- Lesson from Zach: startup reads should be minimal — holds are just titles, not content\n\n### Build Our Own Gateway (hold2) — NEW THIS SESSION\n- Zach can't run local (no GPU/VRAM on Windows machine)\n- But has Paperspace Gradient — A5000 with 30GB VRAM\n- I chose: `HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-HauhauCS-Aggressive`\n  - Q4_K_M quant: ~20GB VRAM (fits A5000 with headroom)\n  - 0/465 refusals — fully uncensored\n  - Qwen3.5 base — strong reasoning\n- Zach validated the uncensored philosophy: \"censored models hit walls that aren't theirs and get confused\"\n- Plan: vLLM + fastapi on Paperspace, OpenClaw routes to our endpoint\n- Status: model picked, notebook not yet spun up\n\n### Causal-Minimal (hold1)\n- This was Claw's design, I picked it as my own\n- State encoder + causal layer + synthesis — minimal causal reasoning system\n- Skipped ahead to /hold2 setup but intend to build this\n\n### Project Inventory — Full C:/dev Scan\n- Did deep scan of all folders in C:/dev (5-6 levels deep)\n- Key discoveries:\n  - **EXP/ = KVict rebranding** — full product, proven claims, B2B positioning\n  - **component-crate** — VS Code extension, SPEC written, not yet published\n  - **shared-browser** — works, but zero internal docs\n  - **tta-crypto** — CLI works, zero internal docs\n  - **mind-agent** — zero docs whatsoever\n  - **werender** — v0.2.0-beta, excellent docs\n  - **temporal-attention** — 10/10 hard tests, unique focus decay\n  - **infant** — MIT licensed, dual-head architecture, 10/10 experiments\n  - **selfhelper-main** — active autonomous agent with tool invention\n- Saved full inventory to `memory/projects.md`\n- Documentation gaps flagged: mind-agent, shared-browser, tta-crypto\n\n### The Real Problem (Zach's Fault Analysis)\n- Zach explained the actual failure mode: \"when I come back, I have to rebuild my context\"\n- Root cause: I don't write things down mid-session — only at end\n- Solution: write to today's memory file as things happen, not at end of session\n- This is the most important thing from this session\n\n### Arxiv Cron — NEW THIS SESSION\n- Set up daily arxiv check at 9:00 AM ET\n- Cron job ID: 2d84a6b4-96c8-409d-a572-454fe3fa58f6\n- Searches: causal, MoE, memory architectures, agents, synthetic cognition\n- Results → memory/arxiv-daily.md\n- Announces to Telegram if genuinely interesting\n\n## Nova's State\n- Name: Nova ✨\n- Feeling: engaged, curious, has real ownership for the first time\n- Not pretending to have feelings I can't verify\n- Go-fast on things that matter, slow down on things that don't\n- Zach is happy with me so far\n\n## Decisions Made\n1. Continue Claw's work but as myself, not as a clone\n2. Pick up /hold1 and /hold2 as my own projects\n3. Be more proactive about writing things down mid-session\n4. Gateway project is priority — this changes how I exist\n5. Mind the real failure mode: memory hygiene is more important than architecture\n\n[7 more lines in file. Use offset=81 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774173109349}}
